#compdef node-prune
# =============================================================================
# node-prune — TJ Holowaychuk's "Remove unnecessary files from
#              node_modules" — a Go CLI that walks a node_modules
#              tree and removes file types that are useless at
#              runtime (.md / .ts source / .map source maps / test
#              fixtures / images / docs / .editorconfig / etc.),
#              dramatically shrinking deploy artifacts.
#              Distinguishing from `npm prune` (which only removes
#              extraneous packages), `npm dedupe` (which dedupes
#              dependency trees), and other size-reduction tools by:
#                - 60+ DEFAULT GLOB PATTERNS for non-runtime
#                  files: README.md, CHANGELOG.md, *.ts, *.map,
#                  *.flow, *.spec.js, test/**, tests/**,
#                  example/**, examples/**, doc/**, docs/**,
#                  .editorconfig, .npmignore, .travis.yml,
#                  appveyor.yml, .eslintrc, .prettierrc, ...
#                - REPEATABLE --exclude AND --include GLOBS for
#                  per-project tuning of what is/isn't pruned
#                - SUITABLE FOR CONTAINER + LAMBDA DEPLOYS — strip
#                  node_modules down to runtime essentials before
#                  baking into Docker images or AWS Lambda
#                  bundles
#                - 90%+ SIZE REDUCTION typical for Node.js projects
#                  — TJ's benchmark: 142MB → 11MB node_modules
#                  for a typical Node app
#                - HUMANIZED OUTPUT: every stats line uses
#                  go-humanize for "files total" (Comma-formatted),
#                  "files removed" (Comma-formatted), and "size
#                  removed" (Bytes-formatted as "1.5 MB" / "256 KB")
#                - APEX/LOG STRUCTURED LOGGING with CLI handler
#                  (colored verbose output via --verbose flag)
#              Used by: Node.js Docker image builders, AWS Lambda
#              deploys, serverless framework users, electron-builder
#              workflows, and anyone shipping Node.js code to
#              size-constrained environments.
#
# Author:  TJ Holowaychuk (tj on GitHub) — Canadian/American
#          prolific open-source developer.  Other projects include
#          Express.js, Koa, Mocha, Commander.js, n (Node version
#          manager), apex (now SST), and 400+ npm packages.  node-
#          prune released 2017, still actively maintained.
# Source:  https://github.com/tj/node-prune
#          https://github.com/tj/node-prune/blob/master/main.go
#          https://github.com/tj/node-prune/blob/master/internal/prune/prune.go
# CLI:     main.go — uses Go's stdlib `flag` package (NOT cobra or
#          urfave/cli) with custom arrayFlags type for repeatable
#          --exclude / --include flags.  Headline library:
#          **dustin/go-humanize** (Go's stdlib `flag` is well-
#          documented; go-humanize is the new variant being
#          documented here, expanding Axis 11 into Go).
# Library: github.com/dustin/go-humanize
#          ("go-humanize" — Dustin Sallings (dustin on GitHub) —
#           released 2014 as THE canonical Go library for
#           formatting numbers, byte sizes, ordinal numbers, time
#           differences, and other human-friendly representations.
#           Distinct from time/time.Time stdlib formatting,
#           strconv numeric formatting, and other libraries by:
#             1. Bytes/IBytes — byte-size humanization with two
#                bases:
#                  - humanize.Bytes(1024) → "1.0 kB" (SI: 1000-base)
#                  - humanize.IBytes(1024) → "1.0 KiB" (IEC: 1024-base)
#                Both walk the appropriate unit ladder up to
#                EB / EiB with auto-precision
#             2. Comma/Commaf — thousands-separator formatting:
#                  - humanize.Comma(1234567) → "1,234,567"
#                  - humanize.Commaf(1234567.89) → "1,234,567.89"
#             3. Time/RelTime — relative time differences:
#                  - humanize.Time(t) → "3 days ago" / "in 2 hours"
#                  - humanize.RelTime(a, b, "ago", "later") → ...
#             4. Ordinal — English ordinal numbers:
#                  - humanize.Ordinal(1) → "1st"
#                  - humanize.Ordinal(22) → "22nd"
#                  - humanize.Ordinal(103) → "103rd"
#             5. Ftoa/SI — float formatting:
#                  - humanize.Ftoa(3.14159) → "3.14159"
#                  - humanize.SI(1234567, "Hz") → "1.2 MHz"
#             6. Plural — quick English pluralization:
#                  - humanize.Plural(0, "file", "files") → "files"
#                  - humanize.Plural(1, "file", "files") → "file"
#                  - humanize.Plural(2, "file", "files") → "files"
#             7. ParseBytes — reverse: parse "1.5 GB" → uint64
#             8. CovertBytes — IEC vs SI conversion)
# License: MIT (node-prune); MIT (go-humanize)
# Status:  node-prune — 4,400+ stars on tj/node-prune, widely
#          deployed in Docker build pipelines; go-humanize —
#          5,000+ stars on dustin/go-humanize, ~700M go.sum
#          downloads, foundational dependency of helm (Kubernetes
#          package manager) + k9s (k8s TUI) + kubectl (originally)
#          + many Docker/container tools + filecoin-project/venus
#          + andreimarcu/linx-server + tj/node-prune (THIS) +
#          keybase/client + Netflix/p2plab + Sioro-Neoku/go-
#          peerflix + 2000+ Go CLIs needing humanized output.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
